<DOC><DOCNO> AP890602-0067 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0636EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     06-02 0454</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,1st Ld-Writethru, a0475,400</SECOND><HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede of 2nd item to DELETE extraneous word; picks up 2nditem, 2nd graf, ``I have</HEAD><HEAD>FDA Approves ``Orphan'' Drug for Anemia Patients</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government has approved a geneticallyengineered drug that can help reduce anemia in patients sufferingfrom kidney failure and may also benefit cancer and AIDS patients.   The drug approved by the Food and Drug Administration Thursdayis a copy of a natural human protein, erythropoietin, whichstimulates the body to produce red blood cells.   Lack of those cells, which carry energy-giving oxygen around thebody, is known as anemia. And since the kidneys produceerythropoietin, patients with kidney failure often develop anemia.   Food and Drug Commissioner Frank Young said that in addition toabout 95,000 kidney patients who should benefit from the new drug,it also may be useful to chronically anemic patients suffering fromother diseases, such as cancer and AIDS.</TEXT><NOTE>___</NOTE><NOTE>Fulton Drops Out of Consideration for HHS Job</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Robert Fulton has dropped out of considerationfor a top welfare post in the Bush administration after strongopposition from Senate conservatives and anti-abortion advocates.   ``I have requested my name be withdrawn, but, of course, I don'tdo that with any joy,'' Fulton, Oklahoma's social servicessecretary, said Thursday.   Health and Human Services Secretary Louis W. Sullivan, who hadwanted Fulton to head the Family Services Administration whichmanages the government's major welfare programs, said he acceptedFulton's decision with ``profound regret.''   Fulton was named as a defendant in a 1985 lawsuit alleging thatfrom 1977 to 1983 several babies born with the severe spinal defectwere denied life-saving surgery at the state hospital. He wasrecently dropped as a defendant.   Fulton, 57, said in Oklahoma City he was ``disturbed about thistype of influence by people who don't mind using smear tactics toget their objective.''   ``They misrepresented what has gone on in the spina bifidacontroversy in Oklahoma and they were able to scare up allianceswith other groups,'' Fulton said.</TEXT><NOTE>___</NOTE><NOTE>Senate Panel Takes Up Bills to Arrange Referendum on Status</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A move that could lead to statehood for PuertoRico is picking up speed in Congress.   A Senate committee on Thursday began considering legislationthat would allow Puerto Rican voters to choose independence,statehood or more autonomy while remaining a U.S. commonwealth.   ``The process we begin today is designed to give the people ofPuerto Rico realistic options from which they can choose and expectthat an option will be implemented,'' said Sen. Bennett Johnston,D-La., chairman of the Committee on Energy and Natural Resources.   The three major political parties on Puerto Rico had requestedthe legislation.</TEXT></DOC>